    pushback: { challenge: "What if lemonade costs $7 and customers can pay any amount ≥ $7?", options: ["Generalize: track all bill denominations in a map. For each payment, greedily use largest bills first for change. O(n × k) where k = number of bill types.","Same greedy works","Always fail without exact change"], correct: 0, explanation: "Variable pricing: maintain map of bill counts. For each payment: compute change needed, greedily dispense largest available bills ≤ change, reduce counts. Fail if exact change impossible. O(n×k) where k=denominations." },
    followup: { question: "What if you want to maximize your cash register balance (not just feasibility)?", options: ["Same greedy for feasibility. Maximizing balance = same thing — you always collect the full bill and give minimum change. Greedy change-giving IS balance-maximizing.","Maximize by refusing small-bill customers","DP needed"], correct: 0, explanation: "Balance = sum of bills received - change given. Change given is minimized by greedy (prefer $10 over three $5s for $20). Same greedy simultaneously ensures feasibility AND maximizes balance." },
